Hawk <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bthepunchingbag74708.showUserPublicProfile?gid=alectosf>AlectoSF</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Training Dummy</span><br>  Posts: 100<br> <font color=#660000>(11/29/02 9:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub83.ezboard.com/fthepunchingbag74708frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2154.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: indeed the new changes make me wonder</span><hr size=1> Forget the G3; get a G4200. I've seen the 64 meg version of those for about $99 now. It's potent. And VERY overclockable.<br>
The 128 meg version is about $120. Either of these will cure what ails you, graphically. <br>
<br>
Pricewatch is a great tool. This machine I type on right now was mostly assembled from stuff garnered there. EMS computing was one of my favorite vendors. <br>
<br>
One thing I wouldn't scrimp on is memory. Do some research here and get GOOD quality memory. You'll need memory bandwidth, and lots of it. Critical decisions that most overlook for saving a few bucks. Buy Corsair or Crucial. You won't be sorry, especially if you're inclined to overclocking. <br>
<br>
AMD is still probably your best bet for a GAMING CPU. The P4 is a hellacious chip...but only if you have massive memory bandwidth, which means the latest RAMBUS modules that your mobo (and bank account) can handle. Nevertheless, the AMD Athlon XPs are far faster in floating point calculations, and that's what 3D games are all about. <br>
<br>
Motherboards are critical. Right now the nVidia nForce2 is probably the best thing going. It's not cheap, but the 2S (I think that's what they're calling it) forgoes the onboard video acceleration, so you can slap that Geforce FX on there without having excess silicon you'll pay for and never use. <br>
<br>
As for accelerator cards, you'll want DX9 compatibility. That means nVidia or ATI. Personally, I think ATIs drivers suck. They have in the past, they do now, they will in the future. It's great hardware, but bad drivers are the norm. Buy nVidia.<br>
<br>
And lastly (hehe), get a GOOD monitor. All the greatest graphics hardware and tasty eye-candy in the latest games aren't worth a damn if you go blind squinting at some piddly shadowmask display screen. Get out there and get a Sony F520! Don't have $1600 for a monitor? Well...hmm...get a good aperture grill 22&quot;. Sony and Mitsubishi/NEC are the only vendors that make their own tubes. Get one from either. They've both very good (and I have both, the Sony is better, but hard to beat the mid to high-end NECs for price/quality). <br>
<br>
One of the advantages of building yourself is ensuring your subsystems are adequate to your needs. You won't have to worry about what garbarge Dell's vendors are lowballing them that month. Also, you can spread costs out over some time. I'm beginning to buy compenents now to complete a machine by July. Course, if you're made of money, just get something from Falcon Northwest or Alienware. Can't lose with those two (aside from devastating your bank account).  <br>
<br>
Good luck and see you all in EQ2 (unless you're a filthy, dirt-grubbing halfling...in which case all you'll see from me is: YOU writhe in pain, taking ungodly damage from some ridiculously overpowered shadowknight innate ability). <br>
<br>
<br>
